==Legal challenges==
[[File:19th Amendment Voting Badge-Harding Coolidge Ticket 1920.png|thumb|upright=.8|"I Cast My First Vote" Nineteenth Amendment Women's Suffrage Badge, Nov. 2, 1920]]

The U.S. Supreme Court unanimously upheld the amendment's validity in ''[[Leser v. Garnett]]''.<ref>{{ussc|258|130|1922}}</ref><ref name="Anzalone 2002">{{Harvnb|Anzalone|2002|p=17}}.</ref> Maryland citizens Mary D. Randolph, "'a colored female citizen' of 331 West Biddle Street,"<ref name=":9">{{Cite magazine|last=Bronson|first=Minnie|date=November 6, 1920|title=Maryland League for State Defense Starts Great Suit|url=https://books.google.com/?id=J9NBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA8-IA138|magazine=The Woman Patriot|volume=4|issue=45|page=2|via=Google Books}}</ref> and Cecilia Street Waters, "a white woman, of 824 North Eutaw Street",<ref name=":9" /> applied for and were granted registration as qualified Baltimore voters on October 12, 1920. To have their names removed from the list of qualified voters, Oscar Leser and others brought suit against the two women on the sole grounds that they were women, arguing that they were not eligible to vote because the Constitution of Maryland limited suffrage to men<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i2i.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/1922-Leser-v.-Garnett-USSC.pdf|title=Leser v. Garnett page 217|date=October 1921|work=Independence Institute}}</ref> and the Maryland legislature had refused to vote to ratify the Nineteenth Amendment. Two months before, on August 26, 1920, the federal government had proclaimed the amendment incorporated into the Constitution.<ref name="Anzalone 2002"/>

Leser stated that the amendment "destroyed State autonomy" because it increased Maryland's electorate without the state's consent. The Supreme Court answered that the Nineteenth Amendment had similar wording to the Fifteenth Amendment, which had expanded state electorates without regard to race for more than 50 years by that time despite being rejected by six states, including Maryland.<ref name="Anzalone 2002"/><ref name="Leser v. Garnett">{{cite web|url=http://openjurist.org/258/us/130/leser-v-garnett|title=258 U.S. 130 - Leser v. Garnett|work=OpenJurist|accessdate=February 7, 2011}}</ref> Leser further argued that the state constitutions in some ratifying states did not allow their legislatures to ratify. The Court replied that state ratification was a federal function granted under [[Article Five of the United States Constitution#Ratification of amendments|Article V of the U.S. Constitution]] and not subject to a state constitution's limitations. Finally, those bringing suit asserted the Nineteenth Amendment was not adopted because Tennessee and West Virginia violated their own rules of procedure. The Court ruled that the point was moot because Connecticut and Vermont had subsequently ratified the amendment, providing a sufficient number of state ratifications to adopt the Nineteenth Amendment even without Tennessee and West Virginia. The Court also ruled that Tennessee's and West Virginia's certifications of their state ratifications was binding and had been duly authenticated by their respective [[Secretary of state (U.S. state government)|Secretaries of State]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Maryland and the 19th Amendment|url=https://www.nps.gov/articles/maryland-and-the-19th-amendment.htm|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=May 4, 2020|language=English|date=September 12, 2019|quote=The court also said that, since the Secretaries of State of Tennessee and West Virginia had accepted the ratifications, that they were necessarily valid.}}</ref> As a result of the Court's ruling, Randolph and Waters were permitted to become registered voters in Baltimore.<ref name="Anzalone 2002"/>

Another challenge to the Nineteenth Amendment's adoption was dismissed by the Supreme Court in ''[[Fairchild v. Hughes]]'',<ref>{{ussc|258|126|1922}}</ref><ref name=fairchildvhughes>{{ussc|name=Fairchild v. Hughes|volume=258|page=126|year=1922}}</ref> because the party bringing the suit, [[Charles S. Fairchild]], came from a state that already allowed women to vote and so Fairchild lacked [[Standing (law)|standing]].

==Effects==
[[File:VOTE poster - Citation Acc 22002 - Archives and Manuscripts - Library of Virginia.jpg|thumb|upright=.8|VOTE poster, League of Women Voters.  c.1920]]
[[File:Ad targeting female votes for 1920 presidential election.jpg|thumb|upright=.8|Ladies Home Journal ad targeting female votes for 1920 presidential election]]

=== Women's voting behavior ===
Ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment enfranchised 26 million American women in time for the 1920 U.S. presidential election.{{sfn|Woloch|1984|p=354}} Many legislators feared that a powerful women's [[Voting bloc|bloc]] would emerge in American politics. This fear led to the passage of such laws as the [[Sheppard–Towner Act|Sheppard–Towner Maternity and Infancy Protection Act]] of 1921, which expanded maternity care during the 1920s.<ref name="Dumenil 1995">{{Harvnb|Dumenil|1995|pp=23–30}}.</ref> Newly enfranchised women and women's groups prioritized a reform agenda rather than party loyalty and their first goal was the Sheppard-Towner Act. It was the first federal social security law and made a dramatic difference before it was allowed to lapse in 1929.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lemons|first=J. Stanley|date=1969|title=The Sheppard-Towner Act: Progressivism in the 1920s|journal=The Journal of American History|volume=55|issue=4|pages=776–786|doi=10.2307/1900152|issn=0021-8723|jstor=1900152}}</ref> Other efforts at the federal level in the early 1920s that related to women labor and women's citizenship rights included the establishment of a Women's Bureau in the [[United States Department of Labor|U.S. Department of Labor]] in 1920 and passage of the [[Cable Act]] in 1922.{{sfn|Baker|2009|p=43}} After the [[1924 United States presidential election|U.S. presidential election in 1924]], politicians realized that the women's bloc they had feared did not actually exist and they did not need to cater to what they considered as "women's issues" after all.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VKGCbw5_P-wC&lpg=PA210&vq=bloc&pg=PA157#v=onepage&q=bloc&f=false|title=Votes Without Leverage: Women in American Electoral Politics, 1920-1970|last=Harvey|first=Anna L.|date=1998-07-13|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521597432|location=|pages=157|language=en}}</ref> The eventual appearance of an American women's voting bloc has been tracked to various dates, depending on the source, from the 1950s<ref name="Moses 1995">{{Harvnb|Moses|Hartmann|1995|pp=xx-xxi}}.</ref> to 1970.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VKGCbw5_P-wC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q=bloc&f=false|title=Votes Without Leverage: Women in American Electoral Politics, 1920-1970|last=Harvey|first=Anna L.|date=1998-07-13|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521597432|location=|pages=10, 210|language=en}}</ref> Around 1980, a nationwide [[Voting gender gap in the United States|gender gap in voting]] had emerged, with women usually favoring the Democratic candidate in presidential elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cawp.rutgers.edu/sites/default/files/resources/ggpresvote.pdf|title=THE GENDER GAP, Voting Choices In Presidential Elections; Fact Sheet|date=2017|website=Center for American Women and Politics (CAWP), Eagleton Institute of Politics, Rutgers University.}}</ref>

According to political scientists J. Kevin Corder and [[Christina Wolbrecht]], few women turned out to vote in the first national elections after the Nineteenth Amendment gave them the right to do so. In 1920, 36 percent of eligible women turned out to vote (compared with 68 percent of men). The low turnout among women was partly due to other barriers to voting, such as literacy tests, long residency requirements and poll taxes. Inexperience with voting and persistent beliefs that voting was inappropriate for women may also have kept turnout low. The participation gap was lowest between men and women in swing states at the time, in states that had closer races such as Missouri and Kentucky, and where barriers to voting were lower.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/08/26/was-womens-suffrage-a-failure-what-new-evidence-tells-us-about-the-first-women-voters/|title=Was women's suffrage a failure? What new evidence tells us about the first women voters|website=Washington Post|access-date=August 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{cite web|url=http://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/politics-international-relations/american-government-politics-and-policy/counting-womens-ballots-female-voters-suffrage-through-new-deal?format=PB|title=Counting Women's Ballots|website=Cambridge University Press|access-date=August 26, 2016}}</ref> By 1960, women were turning out to vote in presidential elections in greater numbers than men and a trend of higher female voting engagement has continued into 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/2010/0818/19th-Amendment-How-far-have-women-in-politics-come-since-1920|title=19th Amendment: How far have women in politics come since 1920?|date=2010-08-18|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2019-05-24|issn=0882-7729}}</ref>

=== Limitations ===
====African-American women====
African-Americans had gained the right to vote, but for 75 percent of them it was granted in name only, as state constitutional loopholes kept them from exercising that right.<ref name=":19">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780253211767|url-access=registration|quote=rosalyn terborg-penn african american women in the struggle for the vote.|title=African American Women in the Struggle for the Vote, 1850-1920|last=Terborg-Penn|first=Rosalyn|date=1998|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253211767|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> Prior to the passage of the amendment, southern politicians held firm in their convictions not to allow African-American women to vote.<ref name=":14">{{Cite journal|last=Nelson|first=Marjory|date=1979|title=women suffrage and race|journal=Off Our Backs|volume=9|issue=10|pages=6–22|issn=0030-0071|jstor=25793145}}</ref> They had to fight to not only secure their own right to vote, but the right of African-American men as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/articles/african-american-women-and-the-nineteenth-amendment.htm|title=African American Women and the Nineteenth Amendment (U.S. National Park Service)|website=nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref>

Three million women south of the [[Mason–Dixon line|Mason-Dixon line]] remained disfranchised after the passage of the amendment.<ref name=":14" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Paul|first=Alice|date=February 16, 1921|title=The White Woman's Burden|url=|journal=The Nation|volume=112|issue=2902|pages=257|via=}}</ref> Election officials regularly obstructed access to the ballot box.<ref name=":26">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/subjects/tellingallamericansstories/upload/CivilRights_VotingRights.pdf|title=Civil Rights in America: Racial Voting Rights|last=Salvatore|first=Susan Cianci|date=June 7, 2019|website=National Park Service}}</ref> As newly enfranchised African-American women attempted to register, officials increased methods of what [[Brent Staples]], in an opinion piece for the ''New York Times'', described as fraud, intimidation, poll taxes, and state violence.<ref name=":15">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/28/opinion/sunday/suffrage-movement-racism-black-women.html|title=Opinion {{!}} How the Suffrage Movement Betrayed Black Women|last=Staples|first=Brent|date=2018-07-28|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-05-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 1926, a group of women attempting to register in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] were beaten by officials.<ref name=":16">{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/news/2018/11/01/how-native-american-vote-evolved/1852110002/|title=How the Native American Vote Evolved|last=Contreras|first=Russell|date=2018-11-01|website=Great Falls Tribune|language=en|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> Incidents such as this, threats of violence and job losses, and legalized prejudicial practices blocked women of color from voting.<ref name=":17">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelily.com/womens-equality-day-celebrates-the-19th-amendment-for-non-white-women-the-fight-to-vote-continued-for-decades/|title=Women's Equality Day celebrates the 19th Amendment. For nonwhite women, the fight to vote continued for decades|last=Williams|first=Sherri|website=The Lily|publisher=The Washington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> Not until the [[Twenty-fourth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Twenty-fourth Amendment]] was adopted in 1962, were Congress and the states prohibited from making voting conditional on poll or other taxes, paving the way to more reforms with the [[Voting Rights Act of 1965]].

African-Americans continued to face barriers preventing them from exercising their vote until a new movement arose in the 1950s and 1960s, which posited voting rights as civil rights.<ref name=":14" /><ref name=":16" /> Nearly a thousand civil rights workers converged on the South to support voting rights as part of Freedom Summer. However, state officials continued to refuse registration until the passage of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which prohibited racial discrimination in voting.<ref name=":26" /><ref name=":17" /> For the first time, states were forbidden from imposing discriminatory restrictions on voting eligibility, and mechanisms were placed allowing the federal government to enforce its provisions.<ref name=":16" />

==== Other minority groups ====
Native Americans were granted citizenship by an Act of Congress in 1924,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/on-this-day-in-1924-all-indians-made-united-states-citizens|title=On this day, all Indians made United States citizens - National Constitution Center|website=National Constitution Center – constitutioncenter.org|language=en|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref> but state policies prohibited them from voting. In 1948, a suit brought by World War II veteran [[Miguel Trujillo]] resulted in Native Americans gaining the right to vote in New Mexico and Arizona,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/local_news/it-s-been-years-since-court-ruled-native-americans-could/article_d0544a48-ef37-56ef-958f-eb81dcf01344.html|title=It's been 70 years since court ruled Native Americans could vote in New Mexico|last=Oxford|first=Andrew|date=2 August 2018|website=Santa Fe New Mexican|access-date=5 June 2019}}</ref> but some states continued to bar them from voting until 1957.<ref name=":16" />

Poll taxes and literacy tests kept Latina women from voting. In Puerto Rico, for example, women did not receive the right to vote until 1929, but was limited to literate women until 1935.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/articles/puerto-rico-women-s-history.htm|title=Puerto Rico and the 19th Amendment (U.S. National Park Service)|last=|first=|date=|website=National Park Service|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> Further, the 1975 extensions of the Voting Rights Act included requiring bilingual ballots and voting materials in certain regions, making it easier for Latina women to vote.<ref name=":16" /><ref name=":17" />

National immigration laws prevented Asians from gaining citizenship until 1952.<ref name="Ault" /><ref name=":16" /><ref name=":17" />

====Other limitations====
After passage of the Nineteenth Amendment, women still faced political limitations. Women had to lobby their state legislators, bring lawsuits, and engage in letter-writing campaigns to earn the right to sit on [[Women in United States juries|juries]]. In California, women won the right to serve on juries four years after passage of the Nineteenth Amendment. In Colorado, it took 33 years. Women continue to face obstacles when running for elective offices, and the Equal Rights Amendment, which would grant women equal rights under the law, has yet to be realized.<ref>{{cite journal|last=McCammon|first=H.|last2=Chaudhuri|first2=S.|last3=Hewitt|first3=L.|last4=Muse|first4=C.|last5=Newman|first5=H.|last6=Smith|first6=C.|last7=Terrell|first7=T.|date=2008|title=Becoming Full Citizens: The U.S. Women's Jury Rights Campaigns, the Pace of Reform, and Strategic Adaptation|journal=American Journal of Sociology|volume=113|issue=4|pages=1104–1147|doi=10.1086/522805}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Brown|first=J.|date=1993|title=The Nineteenth Amendment and Women's Equality|journal=The Yale Law Journal|volume=102|issue=8|pages=2175–2204| doi=10.2307/796863|jstor=796863}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cawp.rutgers.edu/current-numbers|title=Current Numbers|date=2015-06-12|website=CAWP|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/in-2019-womens-rights-are-still-not-explicitly-recognized-in-us-constitution-108150|title=In 2019, women's rights are still not explicitly recognized in US Constitution|last=Rohlinger|first=Deana|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>

==Legacy==
=== League of Women Voters ===
In 1920, about six months before the Nineteenth Amendment was ratified, [[Emma Smith DeVoe]] and Carrie Chapman Catt agreed to merge the [[National American Woman Suffrage Association]] and the [[League of Women Voters|National Council of Women Voters]] to help newly enfranchised women exercise their responsibilities as voters. Originally, only women could join the league; but in 1973 the charter was modified to include men. Today, the [[League of Women Voters]] operates at the local, state, and national level, with over 1,000 local and 50 state leagues, and one territory league in the U.S. Virgin Islands. Some critics and historians question whether creating an organization dedicated to political education rather than political action made sense in the first few years after ratification, suggesting that the League of Women Voters diverted the energy of activists.<ref name=":13" />

=== Equal Rights Amendment ===
{{main|Equal Rights Amendment}}
[[Alice Paul]] and the NWP did not believe the Nineteenth Amendment would be enough to ensure men and women were treated equally, and in 1921 the NWP announced plans to campaign for another amendment which would guarantee equal rights not limited to voting. The first draft of the [[Equal Rights Amendment]], written by Paul and [[Crystal Eastman]] and first named "the [[Lucretia Mott]] Amendment," stated: "No political, civil, or legal disabilities or inequalities on account of sex or on account of marriage, unless applying equally to both sexes, shall exist within the United States or any territory subject to the jurisdiction thereof."<ref name=BaltSun>{{cite news|title=WOMAN'S PARTY ALL READY FOR EQUALITY FIGHT; Removal Of All National and State Discriminations Is Aim. SENATE AND HOUSE TO GET AMENDMENT; A Proposed Constitutional Change To Be Introduced On October 1|last=Henning|first=Arthur Sears|date=September 26, 1921|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|page=1|title-link=:File:Equal Rights Amendment proposed in Congress 1921.jpg}}</ref> Senator [[Charles Curtis]] brought it to Congress that year, but it did not make it to the floor for a vote. It was introduced in every congressional session from 1921 to 1971, usually not making it out of committee.<ref name=crsreport>{{cite web|title=The Proposed Equal Rights Amendment: Contemporary Ratification Issues|date=July 18, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2019|url=https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/R42979.html|website=EveryCRSReport.com}}</ref>

The amendment did not have the full support of women's rights activists, and was opposed by Carrie Catt and the League of Women Voters. Whereas the NWP believed in total equality, even if that meant sacrificing benefits given to women through protective legislation, some groups like the [[Women's Joint Congressional Committee]] and the [[Women's Bureau]] believed that the loss of benefits relating to safety regulations, working conditions, lunch breaks, maternity provisions, and other labor protections would outweigh what would be gained. Labor leaders like Alice Hamilton and [[Mary Anderson (labor leader)|Mary Anderson]] argued that it would set their efforts back and make sacrifices of what progress they had made.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Nancy|last=Cott|title=Feminist Politics in the 1920s: The National Woman's Party |journal=[[Journal of American History]]|year=1984|volume=71|issue=1|pages=43–68|jstor=1899833|doi=10.2307/1899833}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Genora Johnson|last=Dollinger|chapter=Women and Labor Militancy|editor-first=Susan|editor-last=Ware|title=Modern American Women: A Documentary History|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/modernamericanwo00susa_1|chapter-url-access=registration|publisher=McGraw-Hill Higher Education|year=1997|isbn=0-07-071527-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/modernamericanwo00susa_1/page/125 125–126]}}</ref> In response to these concerns, a provision known as "the Hayden rider" was added to the ERA to retain special labor protections for women, and passed the Senate in 1950 and 1953, but failed in the House. In 1958, President [[Dwight Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] called on Congress to pass the amendment, but the Hayden rider was controversial, meeting with opposition from the NWP and others who felt that it undermined its original purpose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.cdlib.org/view?docId=kt6f59n89c&brand=calisphere&doc.view=entire_text|title=Conversations with Alice Paul: Woman Suffrage and the Equal Rights Amendment.|website=cdlib.org|publisher=Suffragists Oral History Project}}</ref><ref name="auto1">{{cite book|last=Harrison|first=Cynthia Ellen|title=On Account of Sex: The Politics of Women's Issues, 1945–1968|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AXlSB6-WpKUC&pg=PA31|year=1989|publisher=University of California Press|pages=31–32|isbn=9780520909304}}</ref>

The growing, productive women's movements of the 1960s and 1970s renewed support for the amendment. U.S. Representative [[Martha Griffiths]] of Michigan reintroduced it in 1971, leading to its approval by the House of Representatives that year. After it passed in the Senate on March 22, 1972, it went to state legislatures for ratification. Congress originally set a deadline of March 22, 1979, by which point at least 38 states needed to ratify the amendment. It reached 35 by 1977, with broad bipartisan support including both major political parties and Presidents [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]], [[Gerald Ford|Ford]], and [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]]. However, when [[Phyllis Schlafly]] mobilized conservative women in opposition, four states rescinded their ratification, although whether a state may do so is disputed.<ref name=chicagotribune31may2018>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/politics/ct-met-equal-rights-amendment-illinois-20180530-story.html|title=Illinois approves Equal Rights Amendment, 36 years after deadline|author1=Rick Pearson|author2=Bill Lukitsch|date=May 31, 2018|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> The amendment did not reach the necessary 38 states by the deadline.<ref name=":13" /> President Carter signed a controversial extension of the deadline to 1982, but that time saw no additional ratifications.

In the 1990s, ERA supporters resumed efforts for ratification, arguing that the pre-deadline ratifications still applied, that the deadline itself can be lifted, and that only three states were needed. Whether the amendment is still before the states for ratification remains disputed, but in 2014 both Virginia and Illinois state senates voted to ratify, although both were blocked in the house chambers. In 2017, 45 years after the amendment was originally submitted to states, the Nevada legislature became the first to ratify it following expiration of the deadlines. Illinois lawmakers followed in 2018.<ref name=chicagotribune31may2018/> Another attempt in Virginia passed the Assembly but was defeated on the state senate floor by one vote.<ref>{{cite web|work=WHSV|url=https://www.whsv.com/content/news/Virginia-Senate-panel-passes-Equal-Rights-Amendment-504158291.html|title=Bid to revive Equal Rights Amendment in Virginia fails by 1 vote|date=February 21, 2019|access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref> The most recent effort to remove the deadline was in early 2019, with proposed legislation from [[Jackie Speier]], accumulating 188 co-sponsors and pending in Congress {{as of|2019|08|lc=yes}}.<ref name=miamiherald26august2019>{{cite web|work=[[Miami Herald]]|date=August 26, 2019|last=Gross|first=Samantha J.|title=99 years ago Florida led in women's suffrage. Are equal rights still a priority?|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article234323672.html|access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref>

=== Commemorations ===
[[File:Portrait Monument Video 01.webmhd.webm|thumb|"The Portrait Monument" (originally "Woman's Movement") by sculptress [[Adelaide Johnson]] in the U.S. Capitol Rotunda]]A 7-and-one-half ton marble slab from a [[Carrara|Carrara, Italy]], quarry carved into statue called the "Portrait Monument"<ref name=":20">{{Cite web|url=https://www.desertsun.com/story/news/nation/2016/09/19/suffrage-movement-susan-b-anthony-portrait-monument-us-capitol-hillary-clinton/88317362/|title=No room for fourth bust on suffragist statue?|last=Goolsby|first=Denise|date=September 19, 2016|website=Desert Sun}}</ref> (originally known as the "Woman's Movement"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/the-portrait-monument-washington-dc|title=The Portrait Monument|website=Atlas Obscura}}</ref>) by sculptress [[Adelaide Johnson]] was unveiled at the [[United States Capitol rotunda|U.S. Capitol Rotunda]] on February 15, 1921, six months after the ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment, on the 101st anniversary of [[Susan B. Anthony]]'s birth, and during the [[National Woman's Party]]'s first post-ratification national convention in Washington, D.C.<ref name=":20" /> The Party presented it as a gift "from the women of the U.S." The monument is installed in the Capitol Rotunda and features busts of Susan B. Anthony, [[Elizabeth Cady Stanton]] and [[Lucretia Mott]]. Over 50 woman's groups with delegates from every state were represented at the dedication ceremony in 1921 that was presided over by [[Jane Addams]]. After the ceremony, the statue was moved temporarily to the Capitol Crypt, where it stood for less than a month until Johnson discovered that an inscription stenciled in gold lettering on the back of the monument had been removed. The inscription read, in part: "Woman, first denied a soul, then called mindless, now arisen declares herself an entity to be reckoned. Spiritually, the woman movement...represents the emancipation of womanhood. The release of the feminine principal in humanity, the moral integration of human evolution come to rescue torn and struggling humanity from its savage self."<ref name=":20" /> Congress denied passage of several bills to move the statue, whose place in the Crypt also held brooms and mops. In 1963, the Crypt was cleaned for an exhibition of several statues including this one, which had been dubbed "The Women in the Bathtub." In 1995 on the 75th anniversary of the Nineteenth Amendment, women's groups renewed congressional interest in the monument and on May 14, 1997, the statue was finally returned to the Rotunda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/suffragist-statue-trapped-broom-closet-75-years-180963274/|title=The Suffragist Statue Trapped in a Broom Closet for 75 Years: The Portrait Monument was a testament to women's struggle for the vote that remained hidden till 1997|last=Boissoneault|first=Lorraine|date=May 13, 2017|website=Smithsonian.com}}</ref>

On August 26, 2016, a monument commemorating Tennessee's role in providing the required 36th state ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment was unveiled in [[Centennial Park (Nashville)]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bliss|first1=Jessica|title=Alan LeQuire's Women Suffrage Monument unveiled in Nashville's Centennial Park|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2016/08/24/alan-lequires-women-suffrage-monument-unveiled-centennial-park/87150580/|accessdate=August 27, 2016|publisher=Nashville Tennessean|date=August 26, 2016}}</ref> The memorial, erected by the Tennessee Suffrage Monument, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|title=Too Few Statues of Women|url=http://tnsuffragemonument.org/too-few-statues-of-women/|website=Tennessee Suffrage Monument, Inc.}}</ref> and created by [[Alan LeQuire]], features likenesses of suffragists who were particularly involved in securing Tennessee's ratification: Carrie Chapman Catt; [[Anne Dallas Dudley]]; Abby Crawford Milton; [[Juno Frankie Pierce]]; and Sue Shelton White.<ref name=":13" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tennesseeencyclopedia.net/entries/woman-suffrage-movement/|title=Woman Suffrage Movement|last=Randal Rust|website=Tennessee Encyclopedia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> In June 2018, the city of [[Knoxville, Tennessee]], unveiled another sculpture by LeQuire, this one depicting 24-year-old freshman state representative Harry T. Burn and his mother. Representative Burn, at the urging of his mother, cast the deciding vote on August 18, 1920, making Tennessee the final state needed for the ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roadsideamerica.com/story/62837|title=Listen to your Mother: a Mom-ument|website=RoadsideAmerica.com}}</ref>

In 2018, Utah launched a campaign called Better Days 2020 to "popularize Utah women's history." One of its first projects was the unveiling on the [[Salt Lake City]] capitol steps of the design for a license plate in recognition of women's suffrage. The commemorative license plate would be available for new or existing car registrations in the state. The year 2020 marks the centennial of the passage of the Nineteenth Amendment, as well as the 150th anniversary of the first women voting in Utah, which was the first state in the nation where women cast a ballot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900034928/new-utah-license-plates-celebrating-utah-womens-suffrage-now-available.html|title=New Utah license plates celebrating Utah women's suffrage now available|last=Burt|first=Spencer|date=October 3, 2018|website=Deseretnews.com}}</ref>

An annual celebration of the passage of the Nineteenth Amendment, known as [[Women's Equality Day]], began on August 26, 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/womens-equality-day|title=Women's Equality Day|website=National Women's History Museum|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> There usually is heightened attention and news media coverage during momentous anniversaries such as the 75th (1995) and 100th (2020), as well as in 2016 because of the presidential election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Womens-Equality-Day|title=Women's Equality Day {{!}} American holiday|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> For the amendment's centennial, several organizations announced large events or exhibits, including the [[National Constitution Center]] and [[National Archives and Records Administration]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/arts/5-things-you-might-not-know-about-the-19th-amendment|title=5 things you might not know about the 19th Amendment|last=Flock|first=Elizabeth|date=2019-09-10|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/15/arts/design/womens-suffrage-movement.html|title=The Complex History of the Women's Suffrage Movement|last=Schuessler|first=Jennifer|date=2019-08-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

=== Popular culture ===
{{multiple image
|total_width=330
|align=right
|direction=horizontal
|footer=[[Lucy Burns]] (left, while in jail) and [[Alice Paul]] (right) of the [[Congressional Union for Woman Suffrage]] were subjects of the film ''[[Iron Jawed Angels]]''.
