}}
{{See also|Women's suffrage in film}}
The Nineteenth Amendment has been featured in a number of songs, films, and television programs. The 1976 song "Sufferin' Till Suffrage" from [[Schoolhouse Rock!]], performed by [[Essra Mohawk]] and written by [[Bob Dorough]] and Tom Yohe, states, in part, "Not a woman here could vote, no matter what age, Then the Nineteenth Amendment struck down that restrictive rule ... Yes the Nineteenth Amendment Struck down that restrictive rule."<ref>{{cite web|last=Litman |first=Kevin |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/44125-best-bob-dorough-schoolhouse-rock-songs |title=Bob Dorough: 9 Best 'Schoolhouse Rock!' Songs from the Composer |publisher=Inverse |date=2018-04-25 |accessdate=2018-11-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schoolhouserock.tv/Sufferin.html |title=Schoolhouse Rock - Sufferin' 'til Suffrage |publisher=Schoolhouserock.tv |date= |accessdate=2018-11-12}}</ref> In 2018, various recording artists released an album called ''27: The Most Perfect Album'', featuring songs inspired by the 27 amendments to the U.S. Constitution; [[Dolly Parton]]'s song inspired by the Nineteenth Amendment is called "A Woman's Right".<ref name="wnycstudios1">{{cite web|url=https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/27-most-perfect-album |title=27: The Most Perfect Album &#124; Radiolab |publisher=WNYC Studios |date=2018-09-19 |accessdate=2018-11-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2018/09/18/dolly-parton-hopes-to-uplift-women-in-new-song-that-highlights-19th-amendment-womens-right-to-vote-listen/ |title=Dolly Parton Hopes to "Uplift Women" in New Song That Highlights 19th Amendment: Women's Right to Vote [Listen] |publisher=Nash Country Daily |date=2018-09-18 |accessdate=2018-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112223521/http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2018/09/18/dolly-parton-hopes-to-uplift-women-in-new-song-that-highlights-19th-amendment-womens-right-to-vote-listen/ |archive-date=November 12, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

''One Woman, One Vote'' is a 1995 PBS documentary narrated by actor [[Susan Sarandon]] chronicling the Seneca Falls Convention through the ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://suffrageandthemedia.org/source/one-woman-one-vote-pbs-documentary/|title=SECONDARY SOURCE - One Woman, One Vote: A PBS Documentary|website=Women's Suffrage and the Media|access-date=May 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517195129/http://suffrageandthemedia.org/source/one-woman-one-vote-pbs-documentary/|archive-date=May 17, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.btchflcks.com/2008/11/one-woman-one-vote-a-documentary-review.html#.XORqKy-ZOqA|title='One Woman, One Vote': A Documentary Review|last=Leab|first=Amber|date=November 4, 2008|website=Bitch Flicks}}</ref> Another documentary was released in 1999 by filmmaker [[Ken Burns]], ''Not For Ourselves Alone: The Story of Elizabeth Cady Stanton & Susan B. Anthony''. It used archival footage and commentary by actors [[Ann Dowd]], [[Julie Harris (actress)|Julie Harris]], [[Sally Kellerman]] and [[Amy Madigan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/not-for-ourselves-alone/|title=Not For Ourselves Alone|last=Burns|first=Ken|website=PBS}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0220253/|title=Not for Ourselves Alone: The Story of Elizabeth Cady Stanton & Susan B. Anthony|website=IMBd}}</ref> In 2013, [[John Green (author)|John Green]], the best-selling author of ''[[The Fault in Our Stars]]'', produced a video entitled ''Women in the 19th Century: Crash Course US History #31'', providing an overview of the women's movement leading to the Nineteenth Amendment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HGEMscZE5dY|title=Women's Suffrage: Crash Course US History #31|last=Green|first=John|website=CrashCourse on YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3957702/|title=Women in the 19th Century|website=IMBd}}</ref>

The 2004 drama ''[[Iron Jawed Angels]]'' depicting suffragists Alice Paul and Lucy Burns, played by actors [[Hilary Swank]] and Frances O’Connor, respectively, as they help secure the Nineteenth Amendment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rightsinfo.org/suffrage-screen-five-films-watch-100-years-since-uk-women-got-vote/|title=Suffrage On Screen: Five Vital Films About How Women Won the Vote|last=McNeil-Walsh|first=Gemma|date=February 6, 2018|website=Rights Info: Human Rights News, Views & Info}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/iron_jawed_angels|title=Iron Jawed Angels|website=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> In August 2018, former U.S. Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] and Academy Award-winning director/producer [[Steven Spielberg]] announced plans to make a television series based on Elaine Weiss's best-selling book, ''The Woman's Hour: The Great Fight to Win the Vote''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/aug/01/hillary-clinton-steven-spielberg-the-womans-hour|title=Hillary Clinton and Steven Spielberg to make TV series on women's suffrage|last=Nevins|first=Jake|date=August 1, 2018|website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2018/08/01/hillary-clinton-steven-spielberg-amblin-tv-series-suffrage-women-vote/|title=Hillary Clinton Is Producing a Television Series on Women's Fight to Win Voting Rights|last=Shoot|first=Brittany|date=August 1, 2018|website=Fortune}}</ref>

